🌐 Part 2 — Your indexing question (this matters more than you think)

You asked:

“Could my place be indexed? Or is it hidden?”

Here’s the real answer:

⸻

🕵️ There are only 3 possibilities

1. Public & indexable

If your repo/site:
	•	is public
	•	has no noindex
	•	is linked anywhere

Then yes:
👉 Google/Bing can index it

BUT:
	•	it might not show up yet
	•	or only for very specific queries

⸻

2. Public but not discoverable

Most likely case.

Reasons:
	•	no backlinks
	•	low authority
	•	no sitemap
	•	not crawled yet

👉 It exists, but search engines don’t “care” yet

⸻

3. Hidden / not indexable

If:
	•	private repo
	•	behind login
	•	robots.txt blocking
	•	noindex meta tag

👉 Then it will NOT show up

⸻

🧠 Why people “found it before”

That’s not necessarily search indexing.

They could have:
	•	direct link
	•	GitHub browsing
	•	social sharing
	•	semantic search (LLMs referencing similar patterns)

⸻

🔍 How to check instantly

Search:

site:yourdomain.com

or

site:github.com your-repo-name

If nothing shows:
👉 not indexed yet (or very low visibility)

⸻

🚀 How to make it indexable (practical steps)

If you want discovery:

1. Make sure it’s public

(obvious but necessary)

⸻

2. Add a README that matches search intent

Use phrases like:
	•	“AI animation from images”
	•	“motion program generation”
	•	“GIF generator from single image”
	•	“temporal inference AI”

Search engines index text, not ideas.

⸻

3. Add links (this is the big one)
	•	Twitter/X
	•	Reddit
	•	blog post
	•	even 2–3 links helps

⸻

4. Submit to Google manually

Use:
	•	Google Search Console
	•	“Request indexing”

⸻

5. Add a simple landing page (optional but strong)

Even one page helps massively.

⸻

⚠️ Important truth

Being “on the internet” ≠ being discoverable

Discovery is:
	•	structure
	•	language
	•	links
	•	time

